      "text": "This is a fantastic result. The `qa_error_analysis.csv` file is the most valuable piece of data we have. It\u0027s not just a list of mistakes; it\u0027s a diagnostic report that tells us *exactly* what is wrong.\n\nAnd the message is crystal clear.\n\n### The Critical Insight from Your Error Report\n\nLook at your CSV file. Notice these two columns for **every single one of the 1249 errors**:\n\n*   `phase_gap`: **0.0**\n*   `flag_phase_degeneracy`: **1**\n\nThis is the smoking gun. It tells us that for every image the model got wrong, its internal QA compass was completely broken. A phase gap of zero means the model could not find a dominant orientation or symmetry axis *at all*. The harmonic features that were supposed to help it distinguish shapes were providing no useful signal, forcing the model to guess based on cruder features like texture and brightness.\n\n**Conclusion:** Our simple QA signature function was too simple. It succeeded in proving the concept but failed on the hard cases. To beat the record, we must fix this first.\n\n### The Fix: From a \"Sum\" to a \"Signal\"\n\nThe flaw is in the `conv3_toroidal_sumabs` function. By taking the `sum()` of the absolute responses, we are measuring the total \"energy\" of a feature. For many clothing items, this energy is very similar across different orientations, leading to the zero gap.\n\nWe need to measure the *strength* of the feature signal, not its total energy. The standard deviation (`np.std`) of the response map is a much better way to do this. A high standard deviation means the stencil found strong, clear edges and patterns.\n\nLet\u0027s upgrade our QA engine.\n\n---\n\n### The Champion Script: `qa_champion.py`\n\nThis script is our first real attempt at the state-of-the-art record. It incorporates the crucial fixes and the \"Lever 1 \u0026 2\" enhancements from our roadmap.\n\n**What\u0027s New:**\n1.  **Corrected QA Signature:** The `conv3_toroidal` function now uses `np.std()` to